text:
Celebration: Lexington Avenue, 66th Street Armory while under construction (Period of 1911, to 1912). Police Commissioner, Harris in silk hat, Cyreus C. Miller, Bronx Borough President next to Mayor Gaynor at the extreme right, 1919-13, Next to Mayor Gaynor.

IDENTIFIED BY MR. DITMAR.
title: Celebrations - Lexington Avenue, 66th Street Armory.

text:
(1)

Lexington Ave., west side, south from East 68th to 66th Streets, showing the Institution for the Instruction of Deaf Mutes occupying the block front, from 68th to 67th Streets. South of same, and utilizing the 67th to 66th Street block is the Seventh Regiment Armory.

October 11, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)

The same. Appearing partially on the right is Thomas Hunter Hall, a unit of Hunter College.

June 12, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

title: Lexington Avenue between 66th and 67th Streets.

text:
Lexington Ave., west side, south from East 66th Street. On the extreme left, appears a portion of St. Vincent Ferrer R.C. Church (at the S.E. corner of East 66th Street).
About ? 1922-24

Lexington Ave., west side, north from and including East 66th Street, showing a crowd congregating for a reason that is unknown to the writer. Occupying the 66th to 67th Street block is the Seventh Regiment Armory.
